Space Stations Built by Radio<br>
<br>
By Charles Q. Choi <br>
April 25, 2003 <br>
<br>
It might be difficult to imagine radio waves can exert enough force to push rock around. Such waves pervade just about every square inch of our planet, carrying music, voice, data and video signals from radio stations, without disturbing so much as a feather. <br>
 <br>
<br>
The best way to build future outposts in deep space could be with force fields produced by a variation of the same energy that powers Earth-based radio stations, NASA-funded researchers predict. <br>
<br>
The researchers envision sanctuaries against the deadly radiation storms of interplanetary space assembled from tens of thousands of tons of extraterrestrial rubble. The structures could be assembled in only a matter of hours by deploying arrays of solar-charged radio wave projectors, according to aerospace engineer Narayanan Komerath at the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta. <br>
<br>
&quot;This would be one of the first steps you need before humans can venture out there,&quot; Komerath told United Press International. <br>
<br>
The structures would serve as vital refuges for astronauts in adventures to investigate and eventually tap into potentially vast resources of water and ore that lie within Earth's neighborhood in the solar system, which in turn could enable missions to Mars and beyond. <br>
<br>
Scientists theorize that thousands of large rocks -- including giant chunks of ice -- are sharing Earth's orbit, either leading our planet around the sun about two months ahead of us, or following Earth about two months behind. <br>
<br>
&quot;It could be a huge breakthrough,&quot; Komerath explained. &quot;As soon as you can have water, and you have all this energy coming from sunlight for free, you can break up the water into fuel, hydrogen fuel, and oxygen for life support,&quot; because water is made of hydrogen and oxygen. &quot;Of course we have water down here, but it's hugely expensive to lift it up to there because you have to fight Earth's gravity.&quot; <br>
<br>
Raw material issues aside, the next major challenge is how to manage the construction. Because the resources are so distant, it would take radio and other transmissions several minutes to get there and back, so it would be impractical to run the operations remotely. <br>
<br>
&quot;We'll have to send people there, or something highly intelligent,&quot; Komerath said. &quot;The big problem is protection from radiation. We don't have an atmosphere there to protect anyone. It's probably the number one problem, and it's months of travel away. Suppose you find out about a solar flare, a giant spike in radiation. There's nothing you could do unless you had very good protection.&quot; <br>
<br>
So the first order of business is to provide radiation-resistant modules to house the construction engineers. &quot;The best way is to be in a cave or behind a thick wall,&quot; Komerath said. &quot;(But) you can't build them and send them out -- they're just so heavy.&quot; <br>
<br>
Komerath and colleagues sought a way to build such a shield without human labor, &quot;since it's too much mass and too many hours of labor. We were looking for a way to automatically build something.&quot; <br>
<br>
Prior experiments had shown ultrasonic waves could hold single droplets in midair. Instead of tinkering with lone particles, the team experimented with thousands of Styrofoam beads, and found they could make the bits cluster into hollow cylinders and more complicated shapes with the right sound emitter setup. <br>
<br>
&quot;If you have waves bouncing back and forth between two walls, they interfere with each other in a way along certain locations,&quot; Komerath said. &quot;If you place a particle of any sort in this field, it will drift towards these locations and just hang around there. If they move out, they'll feel forces that will drive them back.&quot; <br>
<br>
The concept had one major drawback: Sound cannot travel through the vacuum of space. However, the researchers knew certain microscopes use laser beams to push and pull small particles and hold them in place. So they wondered if other kinds of waves could make larger objects move. The longer the wavelength, the bigger the item it could propel. <br>
<br>
&quot;When you use visible light, you move things on the order of micrometers. With microwaves, you are using millimeter objects. But if you want to go to several centimeters, typical of the size of rocks used in construction, you have to go to radio waves,&quot; Komerath said. <br>
<br>
It might be difficult to imagine radio waves can exert enough force to push rock around. After all, such waves pervade just about every square inch of our planet, carrying music, voice, data and video signals from radio stations, without disturbing so much as a feather. <br>
<br>
&quot;Earth's gravity is far more powerful than anything produced by these radio waves,&quot; Komerath explained. For example, 330-foot-wavelength radio waves would exert a force equal only to one-millionth that of Earth's gravity. Yet, assuming rocks about 20 inches in diameter, such force is enough to accelerate them to a speed of about 400 feet per hour, given enough time -- about an hour. <br>
<br>
Komerath explained if you pulverize sandy rock some 46,000 metric tons in mass -- the kind scientists expect to find in near Earth orbit -- four 500-megawatt transmitters could push the rocks into a pipe roughly 160 feet wide and 160 feet long with six-foot-thick walls in only about five hours. Then lasers or focused sunlight could be used to bake the rocks into fused walls. <br>
<br>
&quot;It has very exciting possibilities,&quot; said Robert Cassanova, director of the NASA  Institute of Advanced Concepts in Atlanta. NASA is considering this research for continued funding to develop the idea in greater detail. <br>
<br>
The radio transmitters would not pose much of a technical problem to send into space. &quot;They're really just grids of wire,&quot; Komerath said. The scientists plan to use solar power for the arrays. &quot;The intensity of sunlight once you get away from Earth's atmosphere is 10 times what it is on the surface,&quot; he said. <br>
<br>
The solar power cells would be far more massive than the transmitters. Instead of sending them up, Komerath pointed to NASA research that concluded the cells could be built from the sandy dirt of the moon. &quot;You can build fairly large cells, maybe a kilometer on a side,&quot; Komerath said. <br>
<br>
As soon as the transmitters were placed around the rocks, they could begin collecting solar power for six months before releasing all that stored energy in an hours-long burst. Melting the rocks together would take about 12 hours, Komerath explained. Scientists first would need to pulverize space rock into pebbles that could be shoved around by the force fields. <br>
<br>
&quot;You wouldn't want to just blow up an asteroid and sent everything flying off. Basically, you'd need a robotic hammer,&quot; Komerath said. <br>
<br>
Such a mission would be costly, involving billions of dollars. &quot;It's not something that's going to happen in the next five or 10 years, but there aren't really any showstoppers here,&quot; Komerath said. <br>
<br>
&quot;What does it cost?&quot; he asked. &quot;If you were just doing this, that would be an amount you wouldn't want to think about. But the right question to ask is, 'Why are you doing this?'&quot; <br>
<br>
The answer, Komerath said, is the project would help to establish a space-based economy, which could support even bigger projects in the future, such as colonizing the moon, the asteroid belt and Mars. <br>
<br>
&quot;You have all these resources on Earth that people fight about, but that's a tiny fraction of what's out there,&quot; he noted. &quot;If you can get out there and have a plan to get it, that would be vastly different from today's space program. If you talk about an economy 10 times the size of the economy today, then I think people will invest in that.&quot;  <br>
